Argentina  issued a Treasury bill of
up to $5.7 billion to be bought in several installments by the
central bank, according to a statement in the official  gazette .  The central bank will use international reserves to pay for
the note, issued on April 20. Argentina will use the funds to
pay debt.  The full amount of the note will be paid on maturity in ten
years. Interest will be paid every six months and equals the
rate on the central bankâ€™s international reserves, up to a
maximum of the so-called libor rate minus one percentage point,
according to the notice.  To contact the reporter on this story:
